Our #LG16168_GAGB2, 1866 Winchester King’s Improvement close Copy Chaparral Arms .357 Magnum 20 Inch Color Casehardened Walnut NIB 357 Mag .38 Special 38 Spl Transitional Style close to 1873 Model Navy Arms Competitor / Here is what the manufacturer calls a faithful replica of the famous open top, iron frame receiver patterned on Oliver Winchester’s key employee Nelson King, who hit upon the loading gate and wood forend development, an important step between the 1860 Henry Rifle and the form that traditional lever action rifles embody even today. This fine rifle has a 20  inch Round Carbine length barrel, and it’s chambered chambered in .357 Magnum caliber, interchangeable with .38 Special as well. This well balanced rifle weighs in at only 7 pounds 1 ounce, and its center of gravity is directly centered on the brass shell carrier. Barrel is nicely blued with a hint of purplish hue, marking is Chaparral ~ Repeating Arms / King’s Improvement Patented March 29, 1866, October 16, 1860, in front of the traditional two leaf L aperture and blade rear sight, with the words Cal .357 Mag behind the dovetailed sight base. On the bottom of the receiver beneath the Italicized serial number is Cat. 16170. Upper tang is marked Model 1866. The 10 shot magazine tube, like the barrel, screws, receiver, saddle ring, trigger, buttplate, and lever locking key are blue steel; and the lever and hammer are color casehardened steel. Shell carrier mechanism and ammunition storage plate on the buttplate are solid brass, and the carrier of course mates at the bottom of the receiver. We only have a handful of them. Chaparral Arms, of course, is an Italian based company with relations to two great companies, Charter Arms and Armi San Marco. This rifle’s barrel is inconspicuously marked by its importer, KBI in Harrisburg, PA on the right side barrel flat next to the forend. The KBI / Charles Daly company is sadly defunct. Box, however, is marked Chaparral Arms. Similar Italian-made rifles from competitors Uberti and Navy Arms command prices upwards of $1000 - $1500 per unit. title: For Sale:  Browning Arms Co., "T-Bolt" T2 Rifle, .22LR, MINT Condition
postcontent:
Collectors, Here we have a GORGEOUS Browning Arms Company "T-Bolt" T2 rifle; manufactured in 1966 by FN in Belgium. Chambered for the .22 Long Rifle, the T-Bolt features a unique straight-pull kind of action where the bolt handle is simply pulled backward to open the action and pushed forward to close it. This is the "T2" or Deluxe variation with a lacquer finished hand-checkered walnut stock.   It features a 24" barrel with ramp front sight and and mounted BALVAR 8B scope.   (The  Bausch & Lomb Balvar 8B is a 2.5x8 Variable rifle scope with fine crosshair & dot reticle; gloss finish; the 8B is a very high quality scope that was manufactured in Japan from about 1968 - 1973.)   This near perfect T-Bolt includes the original 5-shot detachable box magazine. Condition is ABSOLUTELY EXCEPTIONAL, NEAR MINT and the rifle retains 100% or the original blue finish. The stock is in ALMOST FLAWLESS Condition, grading 99.8%, with just a couple of super small handling marks. There are no cracks, chips or repairs.   Special note:   This rifle was manufactured in early 1966, which according to a BROWNING ARMS HISTORIAN actually predates the start of the "salt wood" problem years; so there are no worries about hidden rust (nor any evidence of).   The action is smooth and bore excellent.   This superb rifle has been in my family for many years with VERY, VERY minimal use.   Seeking a new home where it will be lovingly used and cared for!!!  (includes original owners manual/instruction booklet)
Serial # 20xxx X6
Price includes Browning Arms Co., T-Bolt T2, with Leather &Vinyl Carrying case and mounted Bausch & Lomb 2.5 x 8 Variable Rifle Scope with lens caps.   Photos upon Request.

More Scope Details...(BALVAR 8B) Bausch and Lomb Scopes:
When people hear the name Bausch and Lomb, they typically think contacts and sunglasses, instead of rifle scopes. However, in the mid 1960's, Bausch and Lomb did venture into the sporting optics market and produce a number of rifle scopes.
During WW1 and WW2, the demand for optical based military equipment reached an all-time high for B&L as military products accounted for almost 70% of all the products they sold. Once the wars were over, Bausch and Lomb saw the optics market change so they changed as well.
In 1962, Bausch and Lomb marketed their first series of rifle scopes, called the Balfour. BAL was an abbreviation for Bausch and Lomb and "four" was the power of the scope. This scope was a success, which led to the introduction of other B&L models, including a very popular variable model called the Balvar (var meaning variable). Many people commonly think that the scope series was a "Balvar" and didn't realize that it was a combination of the abbreviation and the scope settings. Most of the Balvar models were a variable 2.5 to 8 power scopes.
In 1968, Bausch and Lomb released their 2nd generation of scopes known as the "B" series. This series was a continuation of the early BAL models with a "B" appended to the name such as a Balvar 8B. The "B" series did well, leading B&L to release a 3rd generation of scopes known as the Elite 3000 and Elite 4000 series.

title: For Sale:  Hornady Lock-N-Load A.P. Loader
postcontent:
This is a brand new in the box never opened Hornady Reloader. Retail on this thing is $500 and I am asking only $350! Description is below.

Features:
Lock-N-Load® Powder Measure
The only system that uses a full size powder measure that can be reset to another charge or powder with the push of a button. The unique inserts can be preset to the charge you use with the caliber you are loading. The most flexible (and economical) powder system available for progressive presses.

Priming System
The primer slide in the shell carrier receives a primer at the top of the stroke and inserts in the case at the bottom of the stroke. The slide stays in perfect alignment, and is easily changed from large to small. Use the included primer pick-up tubes (large and small) to fill the primer tube.

Lock-N-Load® Bushing System
Switch dies from one caliber to another or change out die stations and begin reloading again in seconds. Once set, dies never needs readjusting. Bushing locks standard 7/8"-14 dies rock-solid in perfect alignment.

Case Activated Powder Drop
Get a charge of powder only when a cartridge is in place. Works with any cartridge, pistol to magnum rifle. Can be manually operated to check powder charge. Install the optional Lock-N-Load powder die for the fastest changeover of all progressive presses. Also fits RCBS measurer.

Five-station Die Platform
Five stations allow for all the variables and still let you use your standard dies — most 7/8"-14 dies and 7/8"-14 powder measures will work.

Universal Ejector
Cases are automatically ejected into the included case catcher.

Automatic Indexing
This very important feature automatically advances shells to the next station with the smoothest indexing of any press in this price range, and rotates every half stroke to lessen the chance of powder spillage.

Case Retainer
Quickly and easily remove and/or replace a case from the shell plate at any point in the cycle without extra retaining buttons. Case retainer fits all calibers.

Large Cartridge Catcher
A large capacity catcher comes standard with the Lock-N-Load AP Press. An extra large capacity catcher which holds up to 1/3 more completed cartridges is available as an option.

*Note: Some manufacturers taper crimp dies may interfere with the ejector wire when they are used in station 5. Hornady New Dimension Taper Crimp Dies are designed to work flawlessly in station 5. If you will be using dies other than Hornady, we suggest that you use our powder through expander and install the taper crimp die in the 4th station. Ejector wires are set at the factory and we DO NOT RECOMMEND adjustment.

I'm selling this TriStar Viper 12 guage semi auto. Its is in very clean and in Very good condition, almost like new, except you can barely see a couple light lines  on the barrel where it looks like it got caught up on a tree limb while walking through the woods.  I had it out only twice and that was a year ago when I was crow hunting.  At that time I activated the 5 year warranty so It still has  4 years left on the warranty!!
It has a Black synthetic stock, and the finish on the receiver and barrel are black also. It has a modified screw in choke and I believe the chokes are the same as benelli chokes. The barrel length is 28".

   It is gas operated, and as many gas operated semi auto's, it does not like those junk Walmart shells that are sold in bulk. It shoots quality ammo such as Winchester and Estate target loads just fine. I have almost a full box of shells that go with the gun.
This cost me $349.99 new, plus $25.00 shipping off of  gunbroker.com and a $25.00 FFL fee, so I have exactly $400.00 in it.  I would like to sell it for $275.00

title: For Sale:  Savage Model 160 Revelation .22 semi-automatic
postcontent:
Savage Model 160 Revelation .22 Long Rifle.  Fourteen round (I think it holds) tube feed.  Good looking walnut stock.  Most of the bluing in good shape. 

With Long Rifle bullets chambers first round and fires with no problem, but has trouble feeding subsequent rounds.  They don't enter the chamber, but hit above the chamber.  If you don't shoot it, but just operate the action, the rounds chamber fine and will cycle through the full magazine without trouble.  I then tried some Longs (not Long Rifle). title: For Sale/Trade:  Czech VZ. 61 SA Skorpion w/ Iraqi shoulder rig
location: Downtown near Ft. WW, Fairbanks, Alaska
postcontent:
For Sale: Czech VZ. 61 SA Skorpion pistol. Chambered in 7.65 Browning (.32 ACP). Comes in original hard case with 10 rnd magazine, 2x 20 rnd magazines, owners manual CD,  dual magazine pouch and a holster with an extender for wearing it either on the belt or as a tactical leg holster. Gun is like new in box (FYI: As with all new Scorpion pistols, the bluing on the gun shows slight wear on the bolt and where the charging lever contacts the receiver. According to CZ USA and as stated in the operators manual this is how they come from the factory Mas they are test fired and sighted in prior to importation which creates this normal wear the first time the bolt is cycled.) 

I am also including a bring-back war souvenir from the First Gulf War as an added collector's bonus. It is an Iraqi made leather shoulder holster rig for a Skorpion. It is somewhat crudely made and is stamped with a encircled star with Arabic in the middle and was made in a shop that used to be located on Al Rasheed St. in downtown Baghdad. Probably belonged to a member of the Republican Guard and was likely recovered from the desert when they fled leaving behind their gear during Operation Desert Storm. I acquired it in a bulk lot of Gulf War Era mil-surp junk from a local guy. While made for one, it isn't fitted to the Skorpion and isn't very functional or practical, but is a nifty historical artifact. You would have to oil it up and condition it properly to get the gun to fit in it. 

Price is $750. Preference given to local private face to face cash transactions in Fairbanks, Alaska. Willing to consider shipping out of state via FFL to FFL transfer where legal to do so. All local and Federal laws apply so if you don't live in a free state (you know who you are) don't ask. Add $80 for shipping, insurance and FFL transfer fee on my end. Payment accepted via PayPal.
